    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-01-30T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-01-30T15:00:00-05:00" n="347"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d347">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00111A.R.–N.C./22: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Uruguay</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Montevideo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-01-30T17:00:00-03:00"
                            >January 30, 1940—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received January 30—4:35 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>11. Department’s circular telegram January 27, 3 p.m. I mentioned this matter to
                        Guani<note n="29" xml:id="d347fn1">Alberto Guani, Uruguayan Minister for
                        Foreign Affairs.</note> today. I have the impression that he is somewhat
                    piqued because Uruguay was not invited to have a representative on the
                    Neutrality Committee. However, I believe that he shares our views regarding the
                    competence of the Committee.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
